E. COLI EHEC - USA (33): (NORTH, SOUTH CAROLINA) O157, COUNTY FAIR PETTING ZOO
******************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 17 Oct 2012
Source: WSOC-TV [summ., edited]
http://www.wsoctv.com/news/news/local/e-coli-cases-tied-outbreak-now-46/nSd9b/


The number of confirmed and probable _E. coli cases linked to the Cleveland County [North Carolina] Fair jumped again on Tuesday, 16 Oct 2012, to 61 cases. 36 of them are children. 25 are adults.

Cleveland County health officials said more people sick with _E. coli_ have a connection to the petting zoo than the food vendors, and in fact, that is the only factor they can find among a group of cases. Health officials do expect the current number to increase because they are not including cases with less-severe symptoms. The incubation period ends after Wednesday, 17 Oct 2012, but secondary cases could still occur from the bacterium being passed from person to person.

Cleveland County Fair Director Calvin Hastings said he doesn't know what the exact source of the outbreak is. He said state health officials advised them to go ahead and treat the petting zoo area like they do every year by plowing it, disinfecting it, laying grass seed, and putting straw over it.

[Byline: Linzi Sheldon]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Based on this posting, a petting zoo appears to be substantially more related to the growing outbreak of enterohemorrhagic _E. coli_ O157 than any specific food.

The state of North Carolina can be located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at http://healthmap.org/r/3Hk_. Cleveland County can be seen on the map at http://www.digital-topo-maps.com/county-map/north-carolina.shtml. - Mod.LL]
